      "role": "user",
      "content": "that's an interesting point about the \"hierarchy of intellect.\" but doesn't that basically just mean we're equating \"intelligence\" with a specific, mostly white, upper-class way of speaking? like, if Sample B uses a dialect or phrasing common in Black communities, are we effectively saying that those communities are inherently less capable of high-level thought just because they don't use \"longitudinal study\" in casual conversation? it feels like the \"competence\" we're talking about is really just a proxy for how well someone fits into a specific racialized social norm.",
